      "**Quaternary ammonium compound** — 3-hydroxy-4-(trimethylammonio)butanoate — synthesized endogenously from the essential amino acids lysine and methionine in liver, kidney, and brain (~75% of body carnitine pool); approximately 25% derived from dietary intake (predominantly red meat, with smaller contributions from poultry, fish, dairy). The endogenous + dietary supply maintains the body carnitine pool of ~20 grams in adults, with ~98% located in skeletal muscle and the remainder distributed across heart, liver, kidney, and other tissues. **Mechanism — the carnitine shuttle (the central role)**: L-carnitine is essential for transport of long-chain fatty acids (chain length 14+ carbons, including palmitic acid C16:0, oleic acid C18:1, others) across the inner mitochondrial membrane to the mitochondrial matrix where β-oxidation occurs. The carnitine shuttle has three components: **(1) CPT1 (carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1)** — the rate-limiting enzyme; located on the outer mitochondrial membrane; conjugates long-chain acyl-CoA molecules to L-carnitine, forming long-chain acyl-carnitine. CPT1 activity is regulated by malonyl-CoA (an intermediate of fatty acid synthesis); high malonyl-CoA inhibits CPT1, preventing simultaneous fatty acid synthesis and oxidation. **(2) Carnitine acyl-carnitine translocase (CACT)** — antiporter on the inner mitochondrial membrane; exchanges long-chain acyl-carnitine (entering the matrix) for free L-carnitine (returning to the intermembrane space). **(3) CPT2 (carnitine palmitoyltransferase 2)** — located on the inner mitochondrial membrane (matrix side); reverses CPT1's reaction: hydrolyzes long-chain acyl-carnitine back to long-chain acyl-CoA + free carnitine. The acyl-CoA then enters β-oxidation. Without functional carnitine shuttle, long-chain fatty acid oxidation cannot occur — energy generation must rely on glucose, ketones, or short/medium-chain fatty acids (which can cross the inner mitochondrial membrane independently). Primary carnitine deficiency (genetic OCTN2 carnitine transporter mutations) and secondary deficiencies (dialysis, valproate, HIV/AIDS, pregnancy) produce clinical syndromes reflecting impaired fatty acid oxidation: cardiomyopathy, hypoketotic hypoglycemia, encephalopathy, muscle weakness. **Mechanism — short and branched-chain fatty acid transport**: parallel mechanism via different carnitine transferases handles short-chain (CrAT, carnitine acetyltransferase) and medium-branched-chain (carnitine octanoyltransferase) fatty acids, though long-chain fatty acid handling is the principal clinical consideration. **Mechanism — acetyl group buffering and the ALCAR variant**: acetyl-L-carnitine (ALCAR) is the acetylated form of L-carnitine; the acetyl group can be donated for cholinergic substrate (acetylcholine synthesis) and can buffer cellular acetyl-CoA pools. ALCAR's BBB penetration is substantially better than L-carnitine base, supporting CNS applications including mild cognitive impairment, depression (some evidence in older adults), and energy support. **Mechanism — propionyl group and the PLCAR variant**: propionyl-L-carnitine (PLCAR) carries a propionyl group that supports anaplerotic substrate flow into the citric acid cycle (propionyl-CoA → succinyl-CoA via vitamin B12-dependent methylmalonyl-CoA mutase). The unique anaplerotic substrate effect is the principal mechanism behind PLCAR's cardiovascular applications (peripheral artery disease, intermittent claudication clinical evidence). **Mechanism — L-carnitine L-tartrate (LCLT) the oral supplement form**: LCLT is a salt form of L-carnitine commonly used in oral supplements (particularly bodybuilding/athletic context); the tartrate salt has reasonable stability and bioavailability. Athletic performance and recovery effects are modest in clinical studies. **Pharmaceutical status**: **L-carnitine is FDA-approved** as Carnitor (levocarnitine) (Sigma-Tau Pharmaceuticals, now Leadiant Biosciences) for primary carnitine deficiency and secondary carnitine deficiency in dialysis patients (hemodialysis) and in valproate-induced carnitine deficiency. ALCAR, PLCAR, and LCLT are sold as dietary supplements. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral L-carnitine bioavailability ~14-18% (dose-dependent; substantially limited by intestinal carrier saturation); IV bioavailability 100%; SubQ/IM bioavailability approaches 100%. Plasma half-life ~17 hours but tissue half-life is days to weeks given the substantial body pool.",
