    sourcingNotes:
      "**FDA-approved as Carnitor (levocarnitine)** (Sigma-Tau Pharmaceuticals, now Leadiant Biosciences) for primary carnitine deficiency and secondary deficiency contexts. Available as oral solution, oral tablet, and IV injection. Off-label use available via integrative medicine and TRT/wellness clinic compounding pharmacies for SubQ/IM injectable formulations. ALCAR (acetyl-L-carnitine), PLCAR (propionyl-L-carnitine), and LCLT (L-carnitine L-tartrate) are widely available as dietary supplements through standard supplement brands; quality varies substantially across supplement sources; established brands with documented purity preferred. ALCAR is the principal CNS-targeted form; PLCAR is the principal cardiovascular-targeted form; L-carnitine base and LCLT are the principal general/athletic forms.",
    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Fatty Acid Mitochondrial Transport Workhorse\n\nL-carnitine is essential for transport of long-chain fatty acids into mitochondria for β-oxidation — without functional carnitine shuttle, long-chain fatty acid oxidation cannot occur. The clinical and supplemental use cases span:\n\n**Primary carnitine deficiency (FDA-approved Carnitor indication)** — genetic OCTN2 carnitine transporter mutations producing systemic carnitine deficiency; treated with high-dose lifelong supplementation (50-100 mg/kg/day)\n\n**Secondary carnitine deficiency (FDA-approved Carnitor indications)** — dialysis-related (hemodialysis removes carnitine), valproate-induced (chronic anticonvulsant therapy depletes carnitine), HIV/AIDS-related, pregnancy-related; treated with replacement supplementation\n\n**Cardiovascular applications** — PLCAR has clinical evidence for peripheral artery disease and intermittent claudication; uses anaplerotic substrate effect via propionyl-CoA → succinyl-CoA pathway\n\n**Cognitive support (ALCAR)** — mild cognitive impairment, depression in older adults, age-related cognitive decline; uses BBB-penetrant ALCAR variant for CNS applications\n\n**Athletic performance and recovery** — modest clinical evidence for endurance performance, recovery, fat oxidation during exercise; effects emerge over weeks of consistent supplementation\n\n**Weight management adjunct** — TRT/wellness clinic and weight loss medicine practice; mechanism via supporting fatty acid oxidation; modest standalone effect; works as adjunct to broader protocols\n\n## The Four-Form Landscape\n\n### L-carnitine (base form)\nFoundational form; broad applications; oral and injectable; the form supplemented in primary deficiency contexts. Carnitor pharmaceutical product.\n\n### Acetyl-L-carnitine (ALCAR)\nAcetylated form; substantially better BBB penetration than L-carnitine base; acetyl group provides direct cholinergic substrate (acetylcholine synthesis); CNS applications: cognitive support, depression in older adults, neuropathic pain.\n\n### Propionyl-L-carnitine (PLCAR)\nPropionylated form; carries propionyl group supporting anaplerotic substrate flow via propionyl-CoA → succinyl-CoA pathway (B12-dependent methylmalonyl-CoA mutase); cardiovascular applications: peripheral artery disease, intermittent claudication; clinical evidence base for PAD.\n\n### L-carnitine L-tartrate (LCLT)\nSalt form; common in oral supplements particularly bodybuilding/athletic context; reasonable stability and bioavailability; muscle-focused applications.\n\nSelection guidance:\n- **Cognitive / depression / neurological** → ALCAR\n- **Cardiovascular / peripheral artery disease** → PLCAR\n- **Athletic / muscle / weight management** → L-carnitine base or LCLT\n- **Primary carnitine deficiency** → L-carnitine base (Carnitor)\n\n## The TMAO Controversy\n\nGut microbiota convert dietary L-carnitine (and dietary choline) to trimethylamine (TMA), which is then oxidized by hepatic FMO3 to trimethylamine-N-oxide (TMAO). Elevated circulating TMAO is associated with cardiovascular risk in some epidemiologic and mechanistic studies — proposed mechanisms include enhanced foam cell formation, platelet hyperreactivity, and endothelial dysfunction.\n\nThe relevance for therapeutic L-carnitine use is debated:\n- Association ≠ causation; TMAO may be a marker rather than driver of CV risk\n- Gut microbiota composition substantially modulates TMA generation — vegans/vegetarians produce less TMA from carnitine than meat-eaters\n- Choline supplementation also generates TMA; lipotropic injections (which contain choline) have similar consideration\n- Antibiotic suppression of gut microbiota substantially reduces TMA generation but is not a sustainable strategy\n- Some research suggests TMAO is more elevated in red meat consumers, suggesting dietary baseline matters more than supplementation\n\nPractical implication: TMAO is a consideration but not a contraindication. Users with substantial CV risk profile or elevated baseline TMAO levels may want to:\n- Consider IV/SubQ/IM administration over oral (bypasses gut microbiota generation)\n- Consider ALCAR or PLCAR over L-carnitine base (different metabolic profiles)\n- Address gut microbiota composition (fiber, fermented foods, polyphenols)\n- Coordinate with cardiology if active CV disease\n\n## Synergies\n**Lipo-C / MIC+B12** — methylation and hepatic lipid handling support; combined fatty acid metabolism and lipid handling. **NAD+** — mitochondrial energy support; downstream of fatty acid oxidation. **GLP-1 agonists (semaglutide, tirzepatide)** — primary weight management intervention. **CoQ10** — mitochondrial energy support. **B12 + folate** — methylation cycle and energy metabolism support. **Resistance training, aerobic exercise** — non-pharmacological foundation that drives fat oxidation directly.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-established via decades of biochemistry research; carnitine shuttle pharmacology and CPT1/CPT2 enzyme function thoroughly characterized. Clinical evidence base strongest for primary carnitine deficiency (FDA-approved indication) and secondary deficiency contexts (dialysis, valproate). PLCAR cardiovascular evidence base substantial in PAD and claudication. ALCAR cognitive support evidence base modest but established. Athletic performance and weight management evidence base modest with effects emerging over weeks. TMAO controversy reflects genuine ongoing scientific debate rather than settled clinical consideration.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational biochemistry well-characterized; FDA-approved Carnitor for deficiency indications; substantial clinical evidence base across multiple form-specific applications; TMAO controversy reflects active research area. Anecdote: substantial supplemental and TRT/wellness clinic use base; community familiarity with form selection (ALCAR for cognitive, PLCAR for CV, base for athletic/weight management); commonly stacked with lipo-c, NAD+, GLP-1 agonists. Decision frame: essential cofactor for long-chain fatty acid mitochondrial transport with FDA-approved pharmaceutical pedigree for deficiency indications; multiple form options with distinct use profiles; cardiovascular context warrants TMAO consideration but not contraindication; pharmaceutical-grade product preferred for clinical deficiency contexts; established supplement brands appropriate for general supplementation; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
