    mechanism:
      "**Synthetic α-melanocyte stimulating hormone (α-MSH) analog** — a 13-amino-acid peptide engineered with two modifications from native α-MSH that dramatically improve pharmacokinetics and receptor selectivity: (1) **norleucine (Nle) substitution at position 4**, replacing methionine and eliminating the oxidation-prone methionine sulfur (substantially improving stability), and (2) **D-phenylalanine (D-Phe) substitution at position 7**, replacing L-phenylalanine and creating resistance to enzymatic degradation (substantially extending half-life from native α-MSH's plasma half-life of seconds). The combined modifications produce a peptide with the same biological effects as native α-MSH but with practical pharmacological exposure for therapeutic use. **Mechanism — MC1R-selective agonism (the central distinguishing feature)**: MT-1 binds and activates the melanocortin-1 receptor (MC1R) with high selectivity vs other melanocortin receptors (MC2R, MC3R, MC4R, MC5R). The MC1R selectivity is the principal pharmacological distinction vs MT-2 (Melanotan-2), which has substantial agonist activity at MC3R, MC4R, and MC5R in addition to MC1R. The narrower receptor profile produces a substantially safer clinical profile — MT-1 lacks the libido effects, sexual response, GI effects, and broader side effect burden associated with MT-2's broader agonism. **Mechanism — MC1R activation on melanocytes (the principal effect)**: MC1R is expressed densely on epidermal melanocytes, hair follicle melanocytes, and ocular melanocytes. MC1R activation by MT-1 drives cAMP elevation via Gαs coupling, which upregulates microphthalmia-associated transcription factor (MITF) — the master transcription factor for melanocyte gene expression. MITF upregulation drives expression of tyrosinase (the rate-limiting enzyme for melanin synthesis), tyrosinase-related protein 1 (TYRP1), and dopachrome tautomerase (DCT) — collectively driving increased melanin synthesis and shifting melanin synthesis toward **eumelanin** (the brown-black photoprotective melanin pigment) over **pheomelanin** (the red-yellow non-photoprotective pigment). The eumelanin/pheomelanin ratio shift is the principal mechanism behind both the cosmetic tanning effect (skin darkening visible as 'tan') and the photoprotective effect (eumelanin absorbs and scatters UV radiation, protecting underlying tissue from photodamage). **Mechanism — clinical photoprotection in erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP)**: EPP is a rare genetic disorder caused by ferrochelatase enzyme deficiency, producing accumulation of protoporphyrin IX in red blood cells, plasma, and skin. Sun exposure activates accumulated porphyrins, generating reactive oxygen species and producing severe pain (described by EPP patients as comparable to severe burn pain) within minutes of sun exposure — a debilitating photosensitivity that substantially impairs quality of life. MT-1 increases eumelanin synthesis in skin → enhanced photoprotection → substantially reduced photosensitivity in EPP patients. The mechanism does not address the underlying ferrochelatase deficiency or porphyrin accumulation but provides protective barrier against UV-mediated porphyrin activation. **Mechanism — anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects (the secondary mechanism layer)**: α-MSH and its analogs have documented anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects in addition to the principal melanin synthesis effects. The secondary mechanisms support theoretical applications beyond cosmetic tanning and EPP photoprotection (vitiligo support, photodamage protection broadly, etc.) though clinical evidence in these contexts is limited. **Pharmaceutical status**: **MT-1 is FDA-approved as Scenesse (afamelanotide)** by Clinuvel Pharmaceuticals, approved in the US in 2019 (earlier in EU) for erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP) photoprotection. Scenesse is the brand-name pharmaceutical formulation. Research peptide format SubQ injection is the off-label / cosmetic tanning use case. **Pharmaceutical formulation**: Scenesse is a **16mg controlled-release SubQ implant** placed subcutaneously by a physician (typically in the upper abdomen above the iliac crest); releases afamelanotide over approximately 2 months; 1-2 implants per year typical for EPP patients. The implant pharmaceutical formulation is distinct from research peptide community SubQ injection use. **Pharmacokinetics — research peptide injection**: half-life ~30-60 minutes plasma; effects on melanin synthesis accumulate over days to weeks; melanin pigmentation persists for weeks to months after dosing cessation as melanocytes complete melanin synthesis cycles.",
