    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The MC1R-Selective Melanocortin\n\nMT-1 (Melanotan-1, afamelanotide) is the safer and more selective member of the melanocortin family used for melanin synthesis stimulation. The MC1R-selective profile produces substantially better safety profile than MT-2 (Melanotan-2) by avoiding the broader MC3R/MC4R/MC5R agonism that drives MT-2's libido effects, sexual response, substantial nausea, and broader side effect burden.\n\nThe practical use case spans:\n\n**Pharmaceutical (FDA-approved): Scenesse for EPP photoprotection** — the first FDA-approved photoprotective pharmaceutical; controlled-release SubQ implant placed by physician 1-2x yearly for erythropoietic protoporphyria patients\n\n**Off-label cosmetic tanning** — research peptide injection for sunless tanning / pre-summer tanning preparation; loading + maintenance dosing pattern\n\n**Theoretical applications** — vitiligo re-pigmentation support, photodamage protection broadly, anti-inflammatory secondary effects\n\n## The Pharmaceutical Story — Clinuvel and Scenesse\n\nClinuvel Pharmaceuticals (Australian pharmaceutical company) developed afamelanotide for EPP photoprotection through a multi-decade clinical development program. The implant pharmaceutical formulation (16mg controlled-release SubQ implant releasing over ~2 months) was chosen for clinical use because:\n- EPP patients require sustained photoprotection rather than transient pigmentation\n- Implant administration removes daily injection burden\n- Pharmaceutical-grade controlled release supports consistent therapeutic levels\n- 1-2 implants per year provides full-year coverage\n\nFDA approval came in 2019 (after EU approval). Scenesse represents the first pharmaceutical melanocortin receptor agonist approved for any indication and validates the MC1R receptor pharmacology framework for clinical applications.\n\n## The Cosmetic Tanning Reality\n\nResearch peptide community use of MT-1 for cosmetic sunless tanning is the principal off-label application. Important practical considerations:\n\n**MT-1 + UV exposure is more effective than MT-1 alone** — the peptide stimulates melanocyte readiness for melanin synthesis, but UV exposure (sun or controlled UV) is the principal driver of actual melanin production. Users seeking maximum tanning effect typically combine MT-1 with controlled sun exposure.\n\n**Eumelanin shift is the photoprotective benefit** — increased eumelanin (brown-black photoprotective melanin) preferentially over pheomelanin (red-yellow non-photoprotective pigment) provides UV photoprotection. Users with naturally pheomelanin-dominant skin (red hair, freckles, fair skin) may experience enhanced eumelanin shift with substantial cosmetic effect.\n\n**Standard sun protection remains essential** — MT-1 does not eliminate UV damage; sunscreen, protective clothing, and sun avoidance remain essential. The MT-1 + standard sun protection combination provides layered protection.\n\n## vs MT-2 — Why MC1R Selectivity Matters\n\nThe principal pharmacological distinction between MT-1 and MT-2 is receptor selectivity:\n\n| Compound | MC1R | MC3R | MC4R | MC5R |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| MT-1 | Strong | Minimal | Minimal | Minimal |\n| MT-2 | Strong | Substantial | Substantial | Moderate |\n\nThe broader MT-2 agonism produces broader effects:\n- **MC4R activation** drives libido / sexual response (the basis for MT-2's reputation in sexual function applications and the substrate for PT-141's MC4R-optimized design)\n- **MC4R activation** drives substantial nausea (the principal MT-2 acute side effect)\n- **MC3R/MC5R activation** drives broader side effect profile (mood effects, autonomic effects, glandular effects)\n\nUsers seeking ONLY tanning / photoprotection effects (not libido / sexual function effects) should prefer MT-1 over MT-2 for the substantially safer profile.\n\n## Synergies\n**MT-2** — combination is uncommon; users typically choose one or the other based on use case. **PT-141** — MC4R-selective for sexual function; complementary if MT-1 used for tanning and PT-141 used for sexual function. **Standard sun protection** (sunscreen, protective clothing, sun avoidance during peak hours) — non-pharmacological foundation that should not be substituted by peptide tanning. **Vitamin D supplementation** — relevant for users reducing sun exposure as part of broader photoprotection strategy.\n\n## Annual Dermatology Surveillance\n\nUsers on extended MT-1 protocols should undergo annual full-body skin examination by dermatologist:\n- Existing nevi assessment for changes (size, color, border, asymmetry)\n- New lesion identification\n- Photodamage assessment\n- Documentation for comparison year-over-year\n\nThe surveillance is appropriate for melanocortin receptor agonist use particularly given theoretical melanocyte activation considerations.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized via decades of melanocortin receptor pharmacology research. Clinical evidence base for EPP photoprotection substantial via Scenesse FDA approval pathway and post-marketing surveillance. Cosmetic tanning evidence base is largely real-world community use rather than randomized trials. Long-term safety profile better characterized than MT-2 given pharmaceutical FDA approval framework.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational MC1R pharmacology well-characterized; FDA-approved Scenesse for EPP with substantial clinical evidence base; safety profile better characterized than MT-2 via pharmaceutical post-marketing surveillance. Anecdote: substantial research peptide community use for cosmetic tanning; community familiarity with loading + maintenance dosing pattern; commonly approached as the safer melanocortin family option vs MT-2. Decision frame: MC1R-selective melanocortin receptor agonist with FDA-approved pharmaceutical pedigree for EPP photoprotection (Scenesse); preferred over MT-2 for users seeking tanning / photoprotection effects without broader melanocortin side effect burden; annual dermatology surveillance prudent for extended use; standard sun protection remains essential alongside MT-1; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
